issues.body:
Background:  When I using mesos plugin and enable 'Use Docker Containerizer Container Type',  mesos will run a docker container as the Jenkins slave,  and also configure 'Idle Termination Minutes' which's value is 1;

Issues:  In some times(one build is running, and another build is pending), two builds of one Jenkins job will run in the same salve which isn't what we want, each build of our Jenkins job need a clean slave environment.  

So, could you guys supply a feature like the feature 'Availability' in Jenkins Docker plugin, then I can use 'docker once retention strategy'

issue_comments.body:
@brugidou  I just updated this PR added container options, can you try it out?

![screen shot 2014-06-27 at 18 34 51](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/37033/3415475/6a97d226-fe21-11e3-9a4e-9e09b9c8c38c.png)

updated comment: replaced a corrected screenshot example

@vinodkone 
@tarnfeld 
@activars 
Thanks guys !
This works i can use the docker image and options functionality. I need a lil more help though!

I am  trying to implement proof of concept Mesos cluster and taking a stab at jenkins farm we have here at Tidemark. I have a mesos cluster running and jenkins mesos plugin configured.
I am used the latest build of the plugin where in i can send docker container image and options to deimos on the slave machine.

We are trying to build a multimodule java project inside and docker container (jenkins slave) 
but when i hit build now on jenkins it never starts building and on the mesos web UI  i notice mesos keep trying to start the container and starts a  spawning tasks for the same job. on the slave node i can see a lot of containers for the same job . Then i have to manually abort the build on jenkins to stop mesos spawning tasks.  

Any help would be appriciated.

@jeid64 Interesting idea, as @vinodkone pointed, we would like to understand your usecase better.

Although, unless there is a very specific reason for using the slave only to perform 1 build job, I would avoid doing that, because it will make things less performant. Specially, in a scenario where you have lot of builds queued up, because acquiring a new slave, and performing a build on it is a relatively expensive operation compared to performing a build on an existing slave. 

Again, as @vinodkone pointed, this can be made configurable.

